Anyways, now that my origin story is out there, I can move unto the next checkpoints & keep them nice & short.

I'm also keeping a diary since a month ago. I write in it whenever I feel like it. I feel like recording my thoughts, especially during these extraordinary times.

author: SJ129
text:
Interesting save room. I'll rest here for a bit and tell of my tale since the last checkpoint.

The first issue I raised last time was of an additional $30 charge because someone seemed to have hacked my cell phone number and accepted some charges. Customer service at the company that charged my carrier HIGHLY uncooperative, so I raised hell with them. After that, despite my protests, some friends who had heard about my situation decided to chip in and foot the $30 for me. Haven't seen any more additional charges since. Thank merciful God for that.

With that out of the way, the second thing I mentioned was of a close online friend of mine who disappeared for a while. She needed some time away, and the first message anyone got from her was directed to me, and it said that she missed me. Of course, being the good listener that I am, I let her tell me what had been going on, and I helped her get through yet another bout of misery.
Then earlier this month, some time late at night, when we were both uninhibited by rational thought, she outright told me her true feelings about me, the hints of which I was oblivious to due to my past shaping me into someone who couldn't afford to get too attached to anyone... until now. This was after a year of knowing each other. I felt quite awkward, as I wasn't really looking for that kind relationship from anyone. It didn't help that she had two exes she broke up with due to them being complete creeps, one of whom I was witness to. Due to that, up until the fateful night, I felt like I had to watch how I say certain things and the frequency at which I did so.
The following days were us getting over how surreal the situation was for the both of us: her because I finally knew how she felt about me, and me because I always thought I wouldn't have a chance with anyone, even if I tried, so I never concerned myself with such pursuits. On one of those nights, she was going through some tumultuous feelings, so I had to quickly think of something to say to her. Even though I couldn't outright say I returned the feeling, me explaining that we needed each other in our lives was enough for her to feel better.
Once she gets a vacation break, she plans on visiting me, and until then, we're working out the details of how that's gonna work out.
Man, what an unexpected turn my life has taken.

Really goes to show how the saying I quoted at the last checkpoint rang true: "Sitting around doing nothing won't get us anywhere!"
Though in my case, it was others who got up and did stuff, and it got me places. If there is any point in me telling these stories, it's in the hopes that you fellows would take action when needed as everyone in my story has by doing what they did and as I have by telling you guys all of this rather than keeping silent.
With that, I wish everyone who reads this a good life.

Checkpoint Log #3

I seem to have stumbled across another of what visitors call “rest points,” though this one seems much different than the two I visited prior.  The landscape appears to be flooded with honey, and hives reach out for what I can only assume to be several kilometers, a stark contrast to the bramble filled cliffsides I came from.  This... hive, so to speak, gives off a different, more adventurous air compared to the soothing aspect of the previous locations, and yet I continue to find entries of past experience left by those who came to this place before me.  Many of them are what can only be considered “checkpoints,” while others simply say things along the lines of “stay awhile and rest.”

These locations intrigue me, and the messages more so.  For the time being, I will leave yet another entry.

The school year is coming to a close once again, meaning that I have less homework to worry about.  I am doing well, staying somewhat mentally stable by drawing, writing, and practicing music.  I wonder when this pandemic will end.

I look forward to the next of these interesting areas, and more importantly, what I will find there.
